============================================================
  QUESTION & ANSWER PAIRS
============================================================

Q1: What is plate tectonics?
A1: Earth's crust is divided into tectonic plates that move
     on the mantle. Their interactions create earthquakes,
     volcanoes, mountains, and ocean trenches over millions
     of years.

Q2: What is the Big Bang?
A2: The Big Bang theory states the universe began from an
     extremely hot, dense point approximately 13.8 billion
     years ago and has been expanding ever since.

Q3: What is inflation?
A3: Inflation is the general rise in price levels over
     time, reducing purchasing power. Caused by excess money
     supply, high demand, or supply shocks. Measured by the
     Consumer Price Index.

Q4: What is natural selection?
A4: Natural selection: individuals with traits better
     suited to their environment survive and reproduce more.
     Over many generations, these traits become more common
     in the population.

Q5: What is gravity?
A5: Gravity is an attractive force between all masses.
     Newton described it as F = Gm1m2/r². Einstein refined
     it as spacetime curvature in general relativity.

============================================================
  ECONOMICS
============================================================

Concept:    Inflation
Category:   Macroeconomics
Definition: General rise in price levels eroding purchasing power
Formula:    Inflation = (CPI_t - CPI_t-1)/CPI_t-1 x 100
Economist:  Irving Fisher
Example:    2022 US inflation hit 9.1%; Fed raised rates to combat it

Concept:    Diminishing Returns
Category:   Microeconomics
Definition: More of one input eventually yields smaller output increases
Formula:    Marginal product falls
Economist:  Turgot/Marshall
Example:    More workers in fixed factory eventually get in each other's way

Concept:    Elasticity
Category:   Microeconomics
Definition: Responsiveness of demand to price change
Formula:    PED = %dQd / %dP
Economist:  Alfred Marshall
Example:    Gasoline demand inelastic; luxury goods elastic

